\nand a stronger transmission!\n\u2014quieter, Stronger, more beautiful\nFisher bodies \u2014with richer upholsteries,\nmore distinctive colors, and wider,\ndeeper seats!\nEvery factor has been considered that\nwould add to the safety, comfort and\nconvenience of the Chevrolet r'^ner.\nCome in today. See this greatest of all\nChevrolets!\nTHE GREATEST\nCHEVROLET\nW CHEVROLET HISTORY\n\nROY H. WOMACK\nIMPERIAL VALLEY DISTRIBUTOR\nEl Centro\nIX IN\nHoltville Calexico\nCECIL G. CLOUSE, Calipatria\nBrawley\nT H E\nPRICE\nRANGE\nOF THE F O U\nLOCAL NETMEN\nCAPTURE MATCH\nFROM BRAWLEY\nr.rawley tennis representatives\nwere given a set-back yesterday at\"\nternoon when a determined group of\nracket wieldors from El Centro came\nfrom behind to nose out their hosts\nby a score of 2. matches to 2. The\ngames were played in Brawley and\nthe local players were out to make\nup ground lost a week previous when\nYuma took their measure.\nJoy and Strickland of El Centro\nstarted tilings going yesterday by\ndrooping their mate-It to \"Waehtler\nd s, elder of IBawloy, 4-0. 0 i and\nThe dust of this match had\ni setth when\nCalls and Linguae of Brawley trim\nmad Edgar and Davies of_El Centro\nin s* night sets. 0-1 and\nThings looked ratl-cr d.-sperate for\ntin local boys at this juncture but\nfor an El t eutro victory took\na di I- -I jump when Shirk of El\nCentre took the measure ef W aehter\n,\u00bbf Brawley, 1-b. b-4 and while\nstt'.-klaiid was aving a rather easy j\n\u2022i\" downing 1.. -ahi rson of 11 raw -1\nby. d-2. (1 4.\nThis left the matches at 2 all and j\n\u2022he deciding tilt still to n'me up.\nThis -:,s between Hate of El Centro\ngainst Thomas of Itrawley. Hale\nv n the first set. <i-5; dropped the,\nsecond to Thomas. 57. but came\nback in a glorious whirlwind finish j\nto put, the match and series on ice\nthe imperial valley press\n;by nn Sti win. This left El h entro\nj with 3 matches, Brawloy 2.\nOther games for the day were:\nImperial lest four matches at t alex\nieo. and Y uni a won on default from\nHoltville. The latter city is now def-\nI initely out of the league and its re\nmaining games on the schedule will\nbe played by Calipntria.\nThe standings of the towns in the\nleague are:\nYunia, (i points.\nCalexico, points.\nEl Centro, 5 points.\nBrawloy. 4 points.\nCalipntria, 4 points.\nImperial, 3 points.\nThe points are figures only on the\nnumber of matches each town lias 1\nwon. Calipntria was given 4 so that\nit would not lie seriously handicap\nped hv its late start in the race.\nYum;: and Imperial won 3 points\neach on defaults n< they were ready\nto play their matches on scheduled\ntime, but no opponents appeared on\nthe courts.\nNEW CHAMPION\nMEANS RETURN\nOF PROSPERITY\nNEW YORK. Foil. 17. (U.PJ\u2014 Reeog\nnition of Jimmy Slattery an world\u2019s\nchampion has put the light heavy\nweight class in the limelight and\npromises to biing a return of pros\nperous era the division enjoyed dur\ning the reign of Jack Delaney and\nPaul Berlenbaeli.\nDuring Tommy I.oughran\u2019s title\ndays there were no contenders cap\nable of giving the champion compe\ntition and light heavy contests drew\nlittle money. With Slatery ns cham\npion. and numerous rivals disputing\nhis right to the title, a return of the\nlog gates which formerly featured\ncompletion in the division is likelv.\nMaxie Roseblooni of New York, so\ncalled \u201cuncrowned ehampinn\u2019\u2019\u2018of the\nclass, has been promised a chance.\nHowever, tlie* state commission has\nruled that he must fight Slntterv at\nBuffalo and this ruling does r.ot suit\nKosenbloom.\nSlattery and Roseubloom have met\nfive times and although the Harlem\nHarlequin has little trouble in de\nfeating other opponents, he lias won\nbut one decision over Mlatterv.\nSo. California\nSport Briefs\nHOLLYWOOD, Feb. 17. (U.R)\nHollywood's Millionaires plav the)\nleague-leading Oakland Plucks to- 1\nnight m what promisess to be one\nof the hardest fought California\nHockey League games of the season j\nhere, ft o Millionaires still ave a]\nchance to get in on the end season)\nmoney which will come to league\nchampions with an oast-west game,'\nand tin are planning to make the j\nmost of it.\n1.0- ANGELES. Feb. 17. (U.R)-\nEli-worth iiios. of Basadon who\nwith Keith (iledhill holds the na- 1\ntioi-al junior doubles title, v.st.rdav I\nwon tin nu n\u2019s singles champ -shlu\nin the fourth annual Los \\ngeles\nopen tennis tournament, lie defeat\ned Lester Stncfcn with scores f 3-ti.\nSi il 7. 2 b, ti 11.\nIJ\u00bb ANO ELKS. Eel). 17. (U.R)\nTwo promising welterweights will\nfight the feature event tonight when\nMatty Mario and Sammy Jackson\nenter the ring in the new Eastsidc\narena. Jackson lias had excellent\nsunt-- as a semi-windup battler lo\ncal!'. while Mario returns to the\nwestern canvas after gaining favor\nable comment in the east.\nLOS AND ELKS, Feb. 17. (U.R)\nTin- Trojan basketeers are expected\nto make it three straight for Uni\nversity of Southern Calif -nia l>v\nwinning from the C. C. 1,. A. team\nwhen they clash here next Saturday\nnight. Another vid uy. after de\nfeating the Bruins 42 to 30 last Sat\nurday night, would make the Tro\nin champions of the southern d\nvision of tlie Pacific Coast confer\nence.\nI S ANGELES. Eeh. 17. (U.R)\nLie Hernandez, Mexican welter-I\nweight, will fight Jack Singer in\nthe 10 romiiT mai event at the Main\nstrci -t athletic eluii lore Saturdav\nnight.\nIJ)> ANGELES. Feb. 17. (U.R)\u2014\nMitb registrations rapidly piling up\nfor tin- 1030 Junior Olympic game-,\nofficials announced today that a\nschedule of meets would In released\nsoon. In h ss than a week, over 1,000\nentries have been made. More than\n25.000 are expected before the son-\nS< '1 l- II ISI'V\nHere And There\nIn Sport World\nCHICAGO, Feb. 17. (U.R)\u2014Jimmy\nMeEarnin started training here to\nday for his bout with Sammy Man\ndell world's lightweight champion,\nhere March L. Maude! will set up\ntraining headquarti rs here t -.nor\nrow.\nCHICA